# CSS Styling Rules

## Never use !important tags in CSS

When styling components, especially when overriding third-party library styles (like Material UI), always increase CSS specificity before resorting to `!important` tags.

### Preferred approaches to increase specificity:

1. **Use double ampersand (`&&`) in styled-components** - This increases specificity by repeating the class selector
2. **Chain class selectors** - Use multiple class selectors to increase specificity
3. **Use more specific selectors** - Target nested elements with more specific paths
4. **Use attribute selectors** - Combine class selectors with attribute selectors when appropriate

### Example:

```css
/* ❌ Bad - Using !important */
.component {
  color: red !important;
}

/* ✅ Good - Using increased specificity */
.component.component {
  color: red;
}

/* ✅ Good - Using double ampersand in styled-components */
export const StyledComponent = styled(Component)`
  && {
    color: red;
  }
`;
```

Only use `!important` as an absolute last resort when all other methods of increasing specificity have been exhausted and documented.
